templates.dispatch:
[System] Execute: You are now responsible for Ravi task {{task.id}}.

Title: {{task.title}}
Priority: {{task.priority}}
Work session: {{session.name}}
Responsible agent: {{session.agentId}}

Operational context:
- effective session cwd: {{session.cwd}}
- contextual worktree: {{worktree.label}}
- parent task: {{task.parentTaskId}}
- effective profile: {{profile.id}}
- primary artifact: {{task.taskDocPath}}

Objective:
{{task.instructions}}

Execution instructions:
- load the `ravi-system-tasks` skill before editing the task
- treat {{task.taskDocPath}} as this task's primary artifact
- write all rich task state in TASK.md first
- for progress, keep `frontmatter.progress` and `frontmatter.progress_note` coherent
- after editing frontmatter/body, use `ravi tasks ...` so the runtime sees the state change

Required flow:
1. Open TASK.md and update frontmatter/body according to the skill.
2. When real work starts or advances, sync:
   ravi tasks report {{task.id}}
3. If blocked, record it in TASK.md and sync:
   ravi tasks block {{task.id}}
4. If terminally failed, record it in TASK.md and sync:
   ravi tasks fail {{task.id}}
5. When complete, record it in TASK.md and sync:
   ravi tasks done {{task.id}}

Rules:
- work in this session until done or blocked
- do not reply by describing the protocol
- use the tasks CLI to update the real task state
- rich task body lives in TASK.md; DB/NATS remain the authoritative state substrate

